    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, a dripping faucet! That is such a classic, annoying problem that even the most stoic goblins would find irritating. You're right, it's a standard compression faucet, which means it's held together by those little rubber washers and metal springs that get worn down by the constant, relentless dripping.\n\nTo fix it, you'll need a few tools: a wrench, a screwdriver, and a new washer (and maybe a new O-ring, though the washer is usually the culprit). First, you have to turn off the water supply under the sink, or at least be prepared to catch a little water if you don't shut it off completely. Then, you unscrew the handle to expose the stem, and that's where the magic happens. You'll see the old, squashed washer sitting there, looking a bit like a sad, flattened goblin head. You pop that out, slide in the new, plump washer, and tighten the nut back up.\n\nOnce you've done that, you turn the water back on and test it. If it still drips, don't panic; sometimes the spring needs replacing too, or the seat needs cleaning. But usually, swapping that washer is like swapping a",
